title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington Model 31 pump shotgun
postcontent:
I would like to sell or trade my 12 gauge Remington Model 31 shotgun in good condition.  Normal wear.1937 model, with checkered stock & forearm, imp-mod choke, 28" barrel.Only selling because I decided to go with 20 gauge.Make a fair offer, or let me know what you have for trade, thanks (low-ballers will not be answered)  (As of 12/5, there were at least 6 Model 31s for sale on Armslist.com nationally. 1 @ $225 and 5 in the $300 to $400 range)
A LITTLE HISTORY:  The Remington Model 31 was introduced in 1931 as a successor to the Remington Model 17, and a direct competitor to the Winchester Model 12. Like the Winchester, the Remington used a milled receiver and was fairly expensive to produce. The Model 31 was, and is, known for one of the slickest and smoothest pump actions called, rather erroneously, a “ball bearing action” even though there are no ball bearings to speak of.  The Model 31 was discontinued in 1949 with less than 200,000 made.  Because of the smooth action, the Model 31 found success on the trap circuit where it dominated the classes.  The 31s only problem was Remington built it too well to compete with the Win. model 12, price wise... so they made the less expensive 870 (more stamped parts) and both the 31 and 12 went bye bye.
